The paper is about question answering using a graph-based recurrent retrieval approach over the Wikipedia graph. This involves natural language processing (NLP) techniques, which are typically covered in the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. Information retrieval (IR) is also a key aspect of the paper, as the model retrieves evidence paragraphs from the graph, which falls under the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category. The paper also uses machine learning techniques, specifically recurrent neural networks, which are covered in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves ranking and selecting the best reasoning path, which can be considered a form of optimization and falls under the cs.LG (Learning) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses a large-scale knowledge graph, which can be considered a form of database, falling under the cs.DB (Databases) sub-category.
